"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-what-to-what-paris-olympics-august-2-caeleb-dressel-regan-smith-teddy-riner\", \"text\": \"Day 7 of the Olympics is here, and it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s shaping up to be a big one. Action continues in the pool and starts on the track, but there are also some fun things to look out for in a few of the lesser-known sports. My daily guide will help you know what to watch.  You should also subscribe toSports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Rings, the podcast where Dan Gartland and I recap everything every night, with new episodes published before NBC\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s prime-time coverage is even over.  Here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be watching Friday, August 2.  This is not a comprehensive list;visit Olympics.comfor a full schedule. All events will stream live on Peacock. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll also be tweeting out a schedule of medal events, Team USA games and other favorites each day.  My Day 7 Olympics viewing guide! A monster day. The big stuff is easy to see.But also: I unironically love trampoline, and this is the only day to see it. And French judo legend Teddy Riner competes. And hello, kayak cross!#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/53t8SaE6qG  It should be another raucous night in the pool, with the race known as the splash and dash, the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 50-meter free. Yes, that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s just one length of the pool, the shortest race at the Olympics. American Caeleb Dressel is the defending Olympic champion, and he has a chance to get back on the podium. The women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 200-meter backstroke should also be a great race, with American Regan Smith gunning for a medal after winning silver in the 200m butterfly Thursday.  And L\\u00c3\\u00a9on Marchand will compete in the 200-meter IM, after we already saw him win golds in the 400 IM,200 breaststroke and 200 flyin front of his home crowd.  Speaking of French athletes, let\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s talk judo. If you haven\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t watched any, this is the day to do it. Heavyweight Teddy Riner is a legend of the sport. Remember we saw him light the Olympic cauldron during the opening ceremony, which should give you some idea of how good he is.  This is his fifth Olympics. He already has four individual medals, plus a gold in the team event, which was new in Tokyo. He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s going for his third individual gold, and the gym will be going crazy. Action starts at 4 a.m. ET, and the finals have been starting around 11:30 a.m. ET (should he make it through).  Trampoline gymnastics! It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s only a one-day event, so this is your only chance to see it. The trampolinists bounce eight meters high (about 26 feet), and routines are made up of 10 separate elements\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094all kinds of flips and twists and tucks\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094scored on difficulty and execution.  They\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll have qualifications and then finals. The women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s finals are at 7:50 a.m. ET and the men at 1:50 p.m. If you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve never seen it, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s worth checking out.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Mitch Goldich is a senior editor for Sports Illustrated, mostly focused on the NFL. He has also covered the Olympics extensively and written on a variety of sports since joining SI in 2014. His work has been published by The New York Times, Baseball Prospectus and Food & Wine, among other outlets. Goldich has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Lehigh University and a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from the Medill School at Northwestern University. He is a Philly native, now living in Boston, and he invented and popularized the octopus, when the same player scores a touchdown and the ensuing two-point conversion.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"